04522nam a22005415i 9780773555655DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2019410549  a97807735556557 a10.1515/97807735556552doi  a(DE-B1597)658027  a(OCoLC)1078636621  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aPR9199.3.P4514bZ62 2018 4aPR9199.3.P4514bZ62 2018 7aBIO0070002bisacsh04aC811/.42231 aPeterman, Michael A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDelicious Mirth :bThe Life and Times of James McCarroll /cMichael A. Peterman. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b19 b&w images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tLeitrim -- tStarting Out -- tSounding the “Magical Flute” -- tThe Suspension Bridge -- tEvading the “Curse of Swift” -- tMaking It and Losing It in Toronto, 1856–66 -- tThe Curse Fulfilled -- tNew York, New York! 1869–92 -- tAppendix A -- tAppendix B -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJames McCarroll (1814–1892) was a talented Irish poet, journalist, humorist, musician, and arts critic who left his mark on nineteenth-century Canada by seemingly engaging with anything topical in every medium. Often writing anonymously or under pseudonyms, McCarroll's best-known nom de plume was "Terry Finnegan," who wrote weekly comic letters to his "cousin" Thomas D'Arcy McGee, offering advice on political and social matters. Yet, since his death, McCarroll's contributions to early Canadian writing and culture have largely been forgotten. Making a case for the recuperation of Canada's lost Irish voice, Delicious Mirth seeks to gather and contextualize the extant fragments of this outspoken and flamboyant entertainer and commentator. Adept in the rich excesses of the Paddy brogue, McCarroll spoke for his beloved but broken country and sought to bring the Irish legacy of expansive prose and lyric poetry to Canada. Following the fluctuations of his personal hope, ambition, and talent through the years, Michael Peterman maps McCarroll's responses to the main events of the late nineteenth century such as Irish emigration, the settlement and growth of Upper Canada, the extension of the railway network, little magazine culture, reform politics and responsible government, the spiritualist movement, nascent Canadian theatre, classical and Celtic folk music, the US Civil War, Confederation, and most notably the Fenian movement, in which he became involved. His travels took him to many places, in particular Peterborough, Cobourg, Niagara Falls, Toronto, Buffalo, and New York City. Revealing a man of immense creative energy and cultural significance who has been lost to Canadian literary historians for over a hundred years, Delicious Mirth shows that McCarroll's life and works are outstanding achievements and deserve fresh attention today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthors, Canadiany19th centuryvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773555655?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773555655423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773555655/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles